    <div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23368#1421079480'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2015-01-12T16:18:00+00:00">Jan 12, 2015 04:18 PM UTC</time> by <b>Thomas Lee</b><a class="anchor" name="1421079480">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>I do indeed have a script that can handle everything that we do with certificates -- well, everything that a script can handle.  I&#39;m not sure that anything that wasn&#39;t custom-made could do it, as we need to put our certificates in multiple places, including copying them into the install tree so they can be checked into version control.  Also, several certificates must be service certs, which seem to be rare outside OSG, to the point that most software has never heard of them (the web interface with which we request InCommon certs is an example; it considers the slash that appears in the CN of a service cert to be an invalid character, so we can never get an InCommon service cert).

The difficulty with xd-login and osg-flock was not a software issue; it was a communications issue.  Mats installs the certificates on those machines in multiple places, and it&#39;s never been particularly clear how he wants cert renewals handled -- does he want to handle it all himself?  Does he want me to renew the certs, put the certs/keys somewhere, and let him know so he can do the rest?  Does he want me to install them (in which case he&#39;d need to tell me everywhere they need to go)?  Does he want both xd-login and osg-flock to be treated the same, or differently?  At present I believe I&#39;ve found all the certificates everywhere on those two machines, and my script knows about them and can check them, but it would be really helpful to have a definitive list from Mats, which he has not been forthcoming with in the past.</pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23368#1417456219'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-01T17:50:19+00:00">Dec 1, 2014 05:50 PM UTC</time> by <b>Scott Teige</b><a class="anchor" name="1417456219">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Tom,
Creating ticket from RQ email
This one is to you. I know you have your own tools to handle things like this, this tool may make your life easier. Your call on using it but do evaluate on ITB infrastructure *only* for now.
Link is&#58;  <a href='http&#58;//svn.racf.bnl.gov/svn/certify/' target='_blank' rel='nofollow'>http&#58;//svn.racf.bnl.gov/svn/certify/</a></pre></div><div class='update_description'><i onclick="document.location='23368#1417455931'; reset_anchor();" class="pull-right icon icon-share"></i><div class="header"><time datetime="2014-12-01T17:45:31+00:00">Dec 1, 2014 05:45 PM UTC</time> by <b>Scott Teige</b><a class="anchor" name="1417455931">&nbsp;</a></div><pre>Tom and Scott,

I was chatting this morning with John Hover who has a automated tool that
checks and renews host certificates. Please take some time to evaluate
this tool, which John will send you a pointer to, and see if it will help
with certificate maintenance.

On a side note, we should consider putting xd-login and flock on our
renewal procedures to prevent issues like the one that happened with
xd-login a few weekends ago.</pre></div><legend>Similar Recent Tickets <small>modified within the last 30 days</small></legend><div id="similar_tickets"><p class="muted">No similar tickets found.</p></div>
